  "title": "Kampf den Faschisten",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7731dd1c49322c0a",
      "text": "\nIn war Ukrainian government appeals to ties from Soviet times"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1fc9cb18569537df",
      "text": "Because of the war, Ukrainian politics of remembrance is also changing. While the past years were characterized by a renunciation of Soviet myths related to the Second World War, attempts are now being made to use them against Russia."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "86284034d262fe17",
      "text": "Commentary by [[Stanislav Serhiienko]] (2022-04-14) [https://jungle.world/artikel/2022/15/kampf-den-faschisten post] (de)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c78d3c0b5ace1b43",
      "text": "In order to persuade the people of Russia to support the war of aggression against Ukraine, President Vladimir Putin evokes the Great Patriotic War and places current events in a historical context with it. This is where both the calls for the \"denazification\" and \"demilitarization\" of Ukraine and the accusation of genocide against the population of the eastern Ukrainian Donbass come from."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d2e4d26bc3bb6318",
      "text": "See also [[“Denazification” of Ukraine]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bed34b7dc029ab51",
      "text": "Ukrainian wartime memory policy, on the other hand, seems improvised and poorly thought out. But one can already see an astonishing development: state memory policy in post-Maidan Ukraine, i.e. after 2014, was based, on the one hand, on questioning Soviet myths and, on the other, on the image of Ukraine as a country that was historically in a struggle against two totalitarianisms. This was linked to an affirmative reference to the ultranationalist Organization of Ukrainian Nationalists (OUN) and its military wing, the Insurgent Army of Ukraine (UPA). However, the UPA's black and red flags, a popular symbol among nationalist-minded Ukrainians after 2014, have since all but disappeared. Even the current fight behind enemy lines is not compared to that of the UPA in World War II. Only the indirect reference in the slogan \"Slava Ukrajini! Herojam Slava!\" (Glory to Ukraine! Glory to the heroes!) remains, because this slogan of the OUN has been the official greeting of the Ukrainian Armed Forces since 2018."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7e03ecc60980cfa0",
      "text": "Instead, in an attempt to win people in Ukraine, as well as in Belarus and Russia, over to the resistance, the same historical images are used that the Kremlin uses. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Selenskyj compares Putin's regime to that of the Nazis and speaks of genocide by the \"occupiers\" against Ukrainians. In his speech to the Israeli parliament in late March, he explicitly drew parallels between the fate of Jews in World War II and that of Ukrainians currently. The Ukrainian government's rhetoric simply reverses the allegations from the Kremlin and turns them against their authors. Equating the brutality of the German occupation with that of the Russian one is also widespread among the Ukrainian population."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "94c6516761f24bad",
      "text": "At the beginning of the war, Selenskyj evoked the unifying experience of the Second World War for Ukrainians, Russians and Belarusians. In one of his speeches, Selenskyj called the current war a \"patriotic war.\" Vitaly Kim, the administrative head of the embattled Mykolaiv region, who became nationally known for his social media appearance, recalled the Soviet war heroes who fought against the Nazis to liberate Mykolaiv. Such rhetoric contrasts with statements made by the Ukrainian ambassador to Germany, Andriy Melnyk, who continues to promote an anti-Soviet nationalist ideology and venerates the leader of the OUN, Stepan Bandera."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7af052a907e7d004",
      "text": "During the war, Ukraine's previous official politics of memory collapsed. The fighting is now taking place in regions where the glorification of the OUN and the UPA historically found little support. Selenskyj tries to use the most unifying historical rhetoric possible that mobilizes all Ukrainian citizens to fight. In a way, it is a return to the [[populism]] of his presidential campaign three years ago and of the first months of his term, when he tried to overcome the socially polarizing historical-political conflicts."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "62e5dad49a3a3853",
      "text": "It is difficult to say whether this will last or whether, in the course of the war or after it, the nationalist politics of memory will return. It could benefit from the hatred that the war feeds. After the failure of anti-war protests in Russia and the realization that the war has at least passive support among Russian citizens, after the images of Mariupol, Butcha or Kramatorsk, hatred for Russians is growing among Ukrainians. Thus, there is a demand for a historiography that portrays the history of Ukraine and Russia as completely separate from each other. The nationalists offer precisely this."
    }
